Customize Stopwords

final_stop <- data.frame(word = c("journalists", "media", "news", "journalist", "journalism", "country", "including", "based", "told", "it’s", "day", "el", "al", "der", "und", "don’t","n","i’m","doesn’t","de","we’ve","id","country’s","that’s","we’re","what’s","you’re","i’ve","ten","myanmar’s","chin","pu",",",".","..","th","s"), lexicon = "custom") %>%
  bind_rows(stop_words)

data_clean <- data_tokenized %>% 
  anti_join(final_stop) %>%
  mutate(word = gsub("[0-9]+", "", word)) %>%  
  filter(word != "") 
## Joining with `by = join_by(word)`

Community Detection

Using Louvain Alogrithm

#Louvain algorithm
word_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(doc_word_pairs %>% filter(n >= 150), directed = FALSE)
clusters <- cluster_louvain(word_graph)

Data Visualization

#plot
ggraph(word_graph, layout = "fr") +
  geom_edge_link(edge_colour = "#d6bea5", edge_alpha = 0.2, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_node_point(aes(color = as.factor(membership(clusters))), size = 2) +
  geom_node_text(aes(label = name), repel = TRUE, size = 2.5, max.overlaps = 1000) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  theme_graph() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Brief Conclusion

The dataset is scraped from nine international NGO journalism websites, each containing articles on global exiled journalism. As attention grows around the human rights issues faced by exiled journalists, the journalism community has shown increasing concern globally. However, academic awareness to support exiled journalists remains disproportionately low. For an upcoming final analysis, I aim to merge this dataset with prior limited scholarly research to create a comprehensive view of current knowledge and especially to highlight what is missing in the global exiled journalism landscape. The result will be used for an introductory section in a potential ICA “blue sky” session.

To explore the dataset, I plan to use unsupervised machine learning method to cluster themes in the text. For this stage (HW5), I construct a co-occurrence network at the article level and apply the Louvain algorithm for community detection.

Although topic modeling is likely a better-suited method for the research goal, this initial homework exercise will provide an useful “hunch” for future topic modeling work.

In this homework, the variable is the “text” of each article. Then at the word level, a network of word pairs is constructed. Given the exponential growth of word-pair combinations, I chose to filter the dataset using frequency cutoffs: individual words appear at least 100 times, and word pairs appear at least 150 times. The cutoff values require further validation for more rigorous future research. Ultimately, I believe topic modeling with qualitative validation will be a more suitable method.

The network results are promising. The co-occurrence network indicates intuitive word pairs, such as “prison” and “flee.” Community clustering also shows interesting patterns: for example, the blue cluster represents topics related to social rights and support systems, with keywords like “support,” “rights,” and “international.” Another red cluster likely reflects political violence and threats faced by exiled journalists, with terms such as “attacks” and “threatened.” However, these two clusters remain relatively broad. Further fine-tuning is necessary to determine whether additional, more nuanced communities might emerge, for subtler thematic distinctions in the data.
